{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter X: Target Costing and Environmental Management Accounting\",\n    \"summary\": \"This chapter delves into the concepts of target costing and environmental management accounting (EMA). It outlines the methodologies and strategies used in target costing, such as determining target costs, identifying cost gaps, and employing multi-disciplinary teams to close these gaps. The chapter also explores the application of target costing in both manufacturing and service industries, highlighting the challenges and solutions. Additionally, it covers life cycle costing (LCC) and its integration with EMA to manage environmental costs effectively. Key examples and case studies, such as Darask Co's D-Paad launch and Volt Co's life-cycle costing analysis for nuclear and wind power stations, provide practical insights into these methodologies.\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The chapter's significance is high due to its comprehensive coverage of target costing and environmental management accounting, which are crucial for both profitability and sustainability in modern business practices.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Target costing is a strategic pricing method used to ensure profitability.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Target costing involves determining the desired profit margin and working backward to establish the maximum allowable cost to achieve that margin. This strategy ensures that the product can be produced profitably at a competitive market price. The process includes deriving a target cost, influenced by external market prices, and designing out costs during the product design phase to meet the acceptable profit margin. While target costing is commonly applied in manufacturing, it presents challenges in service industries [Data: Concepts (178, 200); Relationships (186, 187)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Cost gap identification and reduction are central to target costing.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The cost gap refers to the difference between the current or actual cost of producing a product and the target cost that needs to be achieved to meet the desired profitability. Methods to reduce this gap include reconsidering design to eliminate non-value-added elements, reducing the number of components, using less expensive materials, employing lower-grade staff, investing in new technology, outsourcing, and redesigning workflows. Techniques like tear-down analysis can assist in these methods [Data: Concepts (209, 202, 211); Relationships (195, 197, 266, 267, 268, 269)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Life cycle costing (LCC) provides a comprehensive view of total costs over a product's life.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Life cycle costs include all costs associated with the life of a product, from planning and concept design to distribution and customer service. LCC is a method of calculating the total cost of ownership of a product, asset, or system over its entire life cycle. This comprehensive approach includes initial costs, operating costs, maintenance costs, and disposal costs. LCC is integrated with target costing to ensure all costs are accounted for over the product's life [Data: Concepts (1346, 1592); Relationships (198, 200, 194)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Environmental management accounting (EMA) integrates environmental costs into business decisions.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"EMA involves the identification, collection, and analysis of both physical and monetary information related to environmental activities. It helps management make informed decisions by tracking the use of resources, waste generation, and environment-related costs, earnings, and savings. Techniques like activity-based costing (ABC) and life cycle costing (LCC) are used to manage environmental costs more effectively by identifying cost drivers and reducing their use without reducing output [Data: Concepts (1348, 2052); Relationships (1316, 1317, 1311)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Case studies provide practical insights into target costing and EMA.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes several case studies that illustrate the application of target costing and EMA. For example, Darask Co's D-Paad launch involves using target costing to ensure profitability, with market research determining the price customers are willing to pay at different stages of the product life cycle. Volt Co's life-cycle costing analysis for nuclear and wind power stations provides insights into calculating total life-cycle costs, including operating and decommissioning costs [Data: Concepts (1591, 1583); Relationships (206, 1510, 1511, 1512, 1513, 1502, 1503)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Quizzes and exercises reinforce understanding of key concepts.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes various quizzes and exercises designed to test knowledge and reinforce understanding of target costing and EMA. For instance, the 'Closing Target Cost Gap Quiz' assesses methods to close a target cost gap, while the 'Environmental Management Accounting Quiz' tests knowledge on categorizing environmental costs and understanding EMA principles [Data: Concepts (1354, 1249, 1357); Relationships (202, 1312, 1313)].\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery within a textbook. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., concepts, methodologies, quizzes, examples, cases) within a chapter of a textbook.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a chapter, given a list of concepts, methodologies, formulas and examples that belong to the chapter as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform educators and students about the chapter's content and its key components. The content of this report includes an overview of the chapter's key entities, their definitions, interrelations, and noteworthy details.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: Chapter title - the title is given in the textbook in the format 'Chapter X: title'\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary that outlines the chapter's structure and the main learning outcomes. Focus on the key concepts as mentioned in the learning outcomes, their relevant examples, formulas, and methodologies, and how these elements are related to each other.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the significance of the chapter's content. This score reflects the importance and relevance of the chapter's material in the context of the textbook.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the significance rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the chapter. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"The concept of Expected Value is fundamental to Chapter 8 and is illustrated through multiple examples [Data: Concepts (5, 7, 12); Examples (3, 8, 15, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 5, 7, 12, 3, 8, and 15 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n1,FOCUS GROUP,Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n178,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing\"\" is a pricing strategy used in both manufacturing and service industries. It involves determining the desired profit margin and then working backward to establish the maximum allowable cost to achieve that margin. This strategy ensures that the product can be produced profitably at a competitive market price. The process includes deriving a target cost, which is influenced by external market prices, and designing out costs during the product design phase to meet the acceptable profit margin. While target costing is commonly applied in manufacturing, it presents challenges in service industries. To address these challenges, strategies are suggested to close any target cost gaps that may arise.\",22\n209,\"\"\"COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"COST GAP\"\" refers to the difference between the current or actual cost of producing a product and the target cost that needs to be achieved to meet the desired profitability. For example, in the case of a chair, if the target cost is $96 and the actual cost is $96.95, the cost gap would be $0.95 per chair. This gap represents the amount that needs to be reduced to achieve the target profit.\",5\n1591,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING CHALLENGES AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR DARASK CO'S D-PAAD LAUNCH\"\"\",\"\"\"Darask Co, a global consumer electronics manufacturer, is considering launching a new device, the D-Paad, with a three-year life cycle. The company uses target costing to ensure profitability. Market research has been conducted to determine the price customers are willing to pay at different stages of the product life cycle. The board has set a total product cost limit of $13,000m for the D-Paad. Additionally, the company is exploring the feasibility of using target costing for new retail outlets that will offer free services and repairs.\"\"\",5\n201,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF TARGET COSTING FOR SERVICES\"\"\",\"\"\"Gates & Jobs Co, a tax advisory business, decides to match a competitor's price of $100 for a basic tax return. The target cost is calculated by subtracting the required profit margin from the standard fee, resulting in a target cost of $80. The actual cost of a typical tax return is $100, creating a cost gap of $20. Methods to reduce this gap include reducing the time taken by senior advisers and partners, and reducing overheads.\"\"\",2\n1346,\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Life cycle costs include all costs associated with the life of a product, from planning and concept design to distribution and customer service.\"\"\",2\n202,\"\"\"NARROWING THE TARGET COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing relies on multi-disciplinary teams to reduce the gap between actual and target costs. Methods include reconsidering design to eliminate non-value-added elements, reducing the number of components, using less expensive materials, employing lower-grade staff, investing in new technology, outsourcing, and redesigning workflows. Techniques like tear-down analysis can assist in these methods.\"\"\",2\n207,\"\"\"TARGET COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Target cost\"\" is the estimated total cost that a company aims to achieve to meet its target profit. It represents the maximum allowable cost to produce a product, calculated by subtracting the target profit per unit from the target price.\",2\n200,\"\"\"APPLICATION TO SERVICE INDUSTRIES\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing is most appropriate in manufacturing industries where standard products are made in volume. However, it can also be applied to service industries, though there are challenges such as non-standard products, higher indirect expenses, and potential impacts on customer service or quality.\"\"\",1\n1354,\"\"\"CLOSING TARGET COST GAP QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz assesses methods to close a target cost gap for a product, including substituting raw materials with cheaper versions, and understanding the implications of various cost-reduction strategies.\"\"\",1\n203,\"\"\"INVESTMENT REQUIRED\"\"\",\"\"\"The initial amount of money needed to produce a product, which is a key component in calculating the target cost.\"\"\",1\n208,\"\"\"LIFECYCLE OF PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"The duration over which a product is expected to be produced and sold, which impacts the total investment and profit calculations in target costing.\"\"\",1\n1366,\"\"\"MINIMUM PRODUCTION REQUIRED\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz about the minimum production required to close the target cost gap.\"\"\",1\n210,\"\"\"MULTI-DISCIPLINARY TEAMS\"\"\",\"\"\"Teams composed of members from different functional areas, such as design, engineering, and finance, who collaborate to reduce the cost gap in target costing.\"\"\",1\n1249,\"\"\"TARGET COST CALCULATION QUIZ\"\"\",\"The \"\"TARGET COST CALCULATION QUIZ\"\" involves determining the target cost for a product given its selling price, expected sales volume, and required return on investment. The quiz provides the necessary data to calculate the target cost per unit and tests knowledge on calculating target costs based on expected revenue, required profit, and investment.\",1\n191,\"\"\"TARGET COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"Target cost gap is the difference between the current cost and the target cost, which needs to be closed to achieve cost objectives in target costing.\"\"\",1\n1347,\"\"\"TARGET COST REDUCTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Target cost reduction involves identifying ways to reduce costs to meet a target cost that allows for an acceptable profit margin.\"\"\",1\n1356,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING DESCRIPTION QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on target costing description involves identifying the correct definition of target costing from a set of options. The correct answer describes target costing as identifying the market price of a product and then subtracting the desired profit margin to arrive at the target cost.\"\"\",1\n1363,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING STATEMENTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz about target costing statements, asking which statements about target costing are true.\"\"\",1\n206,\"\"\"TARGET PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"The price at which a product is expected to be sold in the market, used as a starting point in target costing to determine the target cost.\"\"\",1\n211,\"\"\"TEAR-DOWN ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"A method used in target costing to analyze competitors' products by disassembling them to identify cost-saving opportunities.\"\"\",1\n1348,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental Management Accounting (EMA) involves the identification, collection, and analysis of both physical and monetary information related to environmental activities. It helps management make informed decisions by tracking the use of resources, waste generation, and environment-related costs, earnings, and savings.\"\"\",7\n1583,\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING ANALYSIS FOR NUCLEAR AND WIND POWER STATIONS AT VOLT CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Volt Co generates and sells electricity through nuclear and wind power stations. The case involves analyzing the life-cycle costs of these power stations, including operating costs, decommissioning costs, and the total life-cycle cost per gigawatt.\"\"\",4\n1592,\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Life cycle costing (LCC) is a method of calculating the total cost of ownership of a product, asset, or system over its entire life cycle. This comprehensive approach includes initial costs, operating costs, maintenance costs, and disposal costs. Additionally, life cycle costing is a system that tracks and accumulates the actual costs and revenues attributable to each product from development through to abandonment.\"\"\",4\n181,\"\"\"ACCOUNTING FOR ENVIRONMENTAL AND SUSTAINABILITY FACTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"Accounting for environmental and sustainability factors involves discussing the issues organisations face in the management of environmental costs, describing different methods an organisation may use to account for its environmental costs, and discussing the role of the management accountant in supporting the business to develop sustainable practices.\"\"\",2\n197,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental costs\"\" are expenses associated with the environmental impact of an organization's activities, considered in accounting for environmental and sustainability factors. These costs encompass conventional costs, potentially hidden costs, contingent costs, and image and relationship costs. Specifically, they include expenses related to resource consumption, pollution control, and waste management. Environmental costs can be categorized into conventional costs like resource usage, hidden costs embedded in overheads, contingent costs for future liabilities, and image costs related to environmental reputation. Additionally, these costs can be classified by their relation to quality, such as prevention, detection, internal failure, and external failure costs associated with managing environmental impacts.\",8\n2052,\"\"\"IMPORTANCE AND IMPLEMENTATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING AT LITTLE CHEMICAL CO\"\"\",\"\"\"The Little Chemical Co (LCC) faced significant fines and loss of customers due to excessive chemical emissions, prompting a need for better environmental management. The company\u2019s management has recognized the importance of environmental management accounting (EMA) to address and manage environmental costs and impacts effectively. EMA provides both physical and monetary information, utilizing techniques like activity-based costing (ABC) to improve environmental performance and decision-making.\"\"\",2\n317,\"\"\"CONTINGENT COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Contingent costs\"\" are potential costs that may be incurred depending on the outcome of future events. These costs are uncertain and can include legal liabilities, environmental fines, and cleanup costs.\",1\n319,\"\"\"CONVENTIONAL COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Conventional costs\"\" refer to the direct costs associated with production, including raw materials, labor, and manufacturing expenses. These costs also encompass overheads and are typically accounted for in traditional financial statements.\",1\n320,\"\"\"POTENTIALLY HIDDEN COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Potentially hidden costs\"\" are costs that are not immediately apparent or accounted for in traditional financial statements. These can include indirect costs such as regulatory compliance, future disposal costs, environmental degradation, health impacts, and long-term resource depletion.\",1\n318,\"\"\"IMAGE AND RELATIONSHIP COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Image and relationship costs are expenses related to maintaining and improving a company's reputation and relationships with stakeholders. These costs can include public relations efforts, community engagement, and corporate social responsibility initiatives.\"\"\",1\n1247,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL FAILURE COSTS QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz tests knowledge on categorizing environmental failure costs, such as compensation payments, air pollution, and penalties for breaching environmental regulations.\"\"\",1\n1365,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL FAILURE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Quiz about categorizing environmental failure costs by an airline company.\"\"\",1\n1349,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING QUIZ\"\"\",\"The \"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING QUIZ\"\" is designed to test knowledge on various aspects of environmental management accounting (EMA). It includes questions that require participants to categorize fuel costs for a road haulage company under different cost categories, with the correct answer identifying conventional costs as the most appropriate category for fuel costs. Additionally, the quiz covers the purpose of EMA, the types of information it provides, the primary users of EMA information, and the types of data it encompasses.\",2\n1352,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL COST ACCOUNTING TECHNIQUES QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz evaluates knowledge of various management accounting techniques that can be used to account for environmental costs, including flow cost accounting, input/output analysis, life-cycle costing, and activity-based costing.\"\"\",1\n1601,\"\"\"PROPOSALS TO CLOSE COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"Proposals to close the cost gap include introducing 24-hour working in factories, incorporating quality assurance inspections, and increasing sales and marketing spend.\"\"\",1\n1800,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING SYSTEM\"\"\",,1\n1797,\"\"\"METHODS FOR CLOSING THE COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"Methods for closing the cost gap include redesigning the chair, negotiating with suppliers, reducing waste, improving the learning rate, and employing cheaper labour.\"\"\",1\n1593,\"\"\"D-PAAD FEASIBILITY STUDY\"\"\",\"\"\"The feasibility study for the D-Paad includes estimates of sales volumes and prices at different stages of the product life cycle, as well as variable and fixed costs. The study aims to ensure a profit mark-up of 60% and sets a total product cost limit of $13,000m.\"\"\",1\n1594,\"\"\"D-PAAD MARKET RESEARCH ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Market research for the D-Paad estimates sales volumes and prices at various stages of the product life cycle: Introduction (8 million units at $425), Growth (14 million units at $300), Maturity (56 million units at $220), and Decline (2 million units at $120).\"\"\",1\n1595,\"\"\"RETAIL OUTLETS FOR DARASK CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Darask Co is considering opening retail outlets in major cities worldwide. These outlets will sell Darask Co's products and offer free services and repairs. The feasibility of using target costing for these outlets is being discussed.\"\"\",1\n2054,\"\"\"ANALYSIS OF LIFECYCLE COSTS AND STRATEGIC DECISIONS FOR A NEW FITNESS MONITOR\"\"\",\"\"\"Fit Co is considering the development of a new fitness monitor with a commercial life of two years. The case includes cost estimates for research, design, marketing, and manufacturing, and involves strategic decisions based on lifecycle costs.\"\"\",1\n1586,\"\"\"DISPOSAL COST OF SPENT NUCLEAR FUEL\"\"\",\"\"\"The disposal cost of spent nuclear fuel is categorized as an internal failure cost in environmental management accounting (EMA). It is incurred by Volt Co as a result of its activities and is disposed of in a safe manner to ensure it does not become a cost borne by society.\"\"\",1\n2053,\"\"\"PROFIT ANALYSIS AND COST CALCULATION FOR PRODUCT D\"\"\",\"\"\"Scovet Co has identified a market for a new product D and provided estimated sales revenue, contribution percentage, fixed costs, and capital investment. The case involves calculating the total profit over the product's life and the cost per unit, including absorption of all product-specific costs.\"\"\",1\n1584,\"\"\"NUCLEAR STATION LIFE-CYCLE COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle cost per gigawatt of a nuclear station = Total life-cycle costs / Total gigawatts generated over the station's useful life.\"\"\",1\n1585,\"\"\"WIND STATION LIFE-CYCLE COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-cycle cost per gigawatt of a wind station = Total life-cycle costs / Total gigawatts generated over the station's useful life.\"\"\",1\n198,\"\"\"SUSTAINABLE PRACTICES\"\"\",\"\"\"Sustainable practices are business practices that aim to reduce environmental impact and promote sustainability, supported by management accountants in accounting for environmental and sustainability factors.\"\"\",1\n1357,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL COST ACCOUNTING QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on environmental cost accounting involves evaluating statements about environmental costs and their capture in an organization's accounting system. It also touches on input/output analysis and flow cost accounting.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n198,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing can be driven down by directing attention to any costs related to any part of a product's lifecycle, which is the concept of life-cycle costing.\"\"\",33\n190,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves determining the needed Return on Investment (ROI) to calculate the target profit.\"\"\",28\n195,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves identifying and reducing the Cost Gap between the actual cost and the target cost.\"\"\",27\n206,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COSTING CHALLENGES AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR DARASK CO'S D-PAAD LAUNCH\"\"\",\"\"\"The case of Target Costing Challenges and Strategic Planning for Darask Co's D-Paad Launch is related to the concept of Target Costing.\"\"\",27\n187,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF TARGET COSTING FOR SERVICES\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing is illustrated through the Example of Target Costing for Services, where Gates & Jobs Co applies target costing to match a competitor's price for tax returns.\"\"\",24\n200,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Life Cycle Costs are considered in Target costing to ensure all costs are accounted for over the product's life.\"\"\",24\n188,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"NARROWING THE TARGET COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing includes methods for Narrowing the Target Cost Gap, involving multi-disciplinary teams and various cost-reduction strategies.\"\"\",24\n193,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COST\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing aims to determine the Target Cost by subtracting the target profit per unit from the target price.\"\"\",24\n191,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET PROFIT\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves calculating the Target Profit by dividing the total required profit by the number of units to be sold.\"\"\",24\n186,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"APPLICATION TO SERVICE INDUSTRIES\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing is discussed in the context of its application to service industries, highlighting the challenges and considerations.\"\"\",23\n202,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"CLOSING TARGET COST GAP QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The Closing Target Cost Gap Quiz tests knowledge about methods to close a target cost gap using Target Costing principles.\"\"\",23\n189,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"INVESTMENT REQUIRED\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing involves determining the Investment Required to produce a product.\"\"\",23\n194,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFECYCLE OF PRODUCT\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing considers the Lifecycle of Product to impact the total investment and profit calculations.\"\"\",23\n205,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"MINIMUM PRODUCTION REQUIRED\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz about the minimum production required to close the target cost gap is related to the concept of target costing.\"\"\",23\n196,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"MULTI-DISCIPLINARY TEAMS\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing relies on Multi-Disciplinary Teams to reduce the cost gap.\"\"\",23\n199,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COST CALCULATION QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The Target Cost Calculation Quiz tests knowledge on Target Costing.\"\"\",23\n185,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COST GAP\"\"\",\"\"\"Target cost gap is the difference between the current cost and the target cost in target costing.\"\"\",23\n201,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COST REDUCTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Target costing involves Target cost reduction to meet desired profit margins.\"\"\",23\n203,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COSTING DESCRIPTION QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The Target Costing Description Quiz is related to Target costing as it involves identifying the correct definition of target costing.\"\"\",23\n204,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET COSTING STATEMENTS\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz about target costing statements is related to the concept of target costing.\"\"\",23\n192,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TARGET PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing uses the Target Price as a starting point to determine the target cost.\"\"\",23\n197,\"\"\"TARGET COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"TEAR-DOWN ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"The concept of Target Costing includes the use of Tear-Down Analysis to identify cost-saving opportunities.\"\"\",23\n1316,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental management accounting (EMA) uses activity-based costing (ABC) to manage environmental costs more effectively by identifying cost drivers and reducing their use without reducing output.\"\"\",16\n1314,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING ANALYSIS FOR NUCLEAR AND WIND POWER STATIONS AT VOLT CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Life-Cycle Costing Analysis for Nuclear and Wind Power Stations at Volt Co involves considerations of environmental management accounting.\"\"\",11\n1317,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"LIFE CYCLE COSTING\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental management accounting (EMA) uses life cycle costing (LCC) to provide comprehensive cost information over the entire life cycle of environmental activities.\"\"\",11\n229,\"\"\"ACCOUNTING FOR ENVIRONMENTAL AND SUSTAINABILITY FACTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Environmental costs are considered in accounting for environmental and sustainability factors.\"\"\",10\n258,\"\"\"ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"IMPORTANCE AND IMPLEMENTATION OF ENVIRONMENT